definitions: assume something to be true as a basis for reasoning or argument
put forward an idea or theory as a basis for reasoning or discussion
examples: Scientists postulate that dark matter exists throughout the universe
The theory postulates a connection between genetics and behavior patterns
Researchers postulated a new model to explain climate change patterns
The philosopher postulated that free will might be an illusion

definitions: place or arrange your body in a particular position for effect
behave in a way that is intended to impress or mislead others
examples: The model postured gracefully for the fashion photographer's camera shoot
Soldiers posture at attention during the morning inspection ceremony
Politicians often posture about issues to gain voter support
He's just posturing to impress his new colleagues at work

definitions: shape clay into pots or other objects using hands or tools
move around without hurrying in a relaxed way doing small tasks
examples: She potters at the wheel creating beautiful ceramic bowls daily
My grandmother learned to potter from her mother in childhood
He potters around the garden on sunny Sunday afternoon hours
I spent the morning pottering in the garage organizing old tools

definitions: put something into a small bag or pocket-like container for storage
make something bulge out or form a pocket-like shape or cavity
examples: The kangaroo pouched her baby joey for warmth and protection
Travelers pouch their passports in special security wallets for safety
His cheeks pouched out when he filled them with air
The fabric pouched at the seams from too much weight

definitions: do something repeatedly to improve skill or prepare for performance
work in a profession especially medicine or law requiring special training
examples: Musicians practise scales every day to maintain their technical skills
The team practises twice weekly before the championship game begins
She practises medicine at the local community health center downtown
Lawyers who practise criminal law often work long unpredictable hours

definitions: play a mischievous trick on someone as a joke or for amusement
examples: Students pranked their teacher by rearranging all the classroom furniture
My brother pranked me by putting salt in the sugar container

definitions: catch prawns by fishing with nets or traps in coastal waters
examples: Local fishermen prawn in the shallow waters near the coral reef
We spent the weekend prawning along the eastern coastline with nets

definitions: speak or write as an introduction before the main part of something
examples: The speaker preambled with thanks before delivering the keynote address
Don't preamble too much before getting to your main point

definitions: come before something in time or order of importance or sequence
go in front of or ahead of someone or something in position
examples: The appetizers precede the main course in formal dinner service
A major earthquake preceded the volcanic eruption by several hours
The security team precedes the president wherever she travels for safety
The parade float preceded the marching band down Main Street

definitions: cause something to happen suddenly or too soon without careful thought
fall from clouds as rain snow or hail in weather systems
cause a substance to separate from a solution as a solid
examples: His careless remarks precipitated a crisis in diplomatic relations overnight
The scandal precipitated the minister's resignation from the cabinet position
Moisture precipitates when warm air meets a cold surface rapidly
Heavy rain precipitated throughout the night causing minor street flooding
Adding acid precipitates the protein from the milk solution completely
The chemist precipitated silver chloride by mixing the two solutions

definitions: prevent something from happening or make it impossible for someone to do something
examples: Heavy snow precluded any possibility of driving to work today
His criminal record precludes him from working in financial services

definitions: prepare or influence someone or something in advance for a particular purpose or state
examples: The therapist preconditioned patients for hypnosis through relaxation exercises first
Athletes precondition their bodies with stretching before intense training sessions

definitions: exist or occur at a date earlier than something else in history
mark with a date that is earlier than the actual date
examples: These cave paintings predate written history by thousands of years
The castle predates the town that grew up around it
She predated the check to avoid a late payment penalty fee
Don't predate legal documents as this could cause serious problems

definitions: base something on a particular belief principle or condition as foundation
state declare or affirm something about the subject of a sentence
examples: The theory predicates its conclusions on extensive laboratory research data
They predicate their business model on continuous technological innovation trends
The philosopher predicates that all humans possess inherent dignity equally
Grammar rules predicate certain relationships between subjects and their verbs

definitions: make someone liable or inclined to a specified attitude action or condition beforehand
examples: Genetics may predispose some individuals to certain types of cancer
Early childhood experiences predispose us to specific behavioral patterns later

definitions: be the strongest or main element that has greater power or influence over others
examples: Oak trees predominate in this ancient forest ecosystem throughout the region
Conservative views predominate among the older generation in rural communities

definitions: take action to prevent something happening by doing something first
replace a scheduled television program with something considered more important
examples: The company preempted competitors by launching their product two months early
Military forces preempted the attack by striking enemy positions first
News networks preempted regular programming to cover the breaking story live
The president's speech preempted the scheduled game show this evening

definitions: provide an introduction to something spoken or written with preliminary remarks or explanation
examples: The author prefaced her novel with acknowledgments to family members
He prefaced his criticism with several compliments about the presentation

definitions: add letters or words to the beginning of a word or name
examples: In chemistry we prefix 'mono' to indicate a single atom element
The company prefixes all employee ID numbers with department codes

definitions: cause harm to a legal case or someone's rights or claims
give someone an unfair bias against or in favor of something
examples: Discussing the case publicly might prejudice the jury's fair deliberation process
The leaked evidence could prejudice the defendant's right to fair trial
Don't let one bad experience prejudice you against all city restaurants
Media coverage may prejudice public opinion before all facts emerge

definitions: serve as an introduction or preliminary to something more important that follows
examples: Dark clouds prelude the approaching thunderstorm that will arrive soon
These negotiations prelude a major peace agreement between the two nations

definitions: give the first public performance or showing of a play film or musical work
examples: The movie premieres at the international film festival next Friday evening
The orchestra will premiere the composer's new symphony this weekend

definitions: order medicine or treatment for a patient as a medical professional
state authoritatively what should be done in particular circumstances as a rule
examples: The doctor prescribed antibiotics for the severe throat infection yesterday
Physicians prescribe pain medication carefully to avoid dependency issues developing
Safety regulations prescribe specific procedures for handling hazardous chemical materials
The constitution prescribes how government powers should be distributed equally

definitions: be in charge of a meeting ceremony or other formal event as leader
examples: The chief justice presides over the Supreme Court proceedings with authority
She will preside at tomorrow's board meeting as the new chairperson

definitions: suppose that something is true without having definite proof of it
be arrogant enough to do something without permission or right
examples: I presume you've already eaten lunch since it's past two o'clock
The court presumes innocence until guilt is proven beyond reasonable doubt
How dare you presume to speak on behalf of everyone here
Don't presume to tell me how to raise my own children

definitions: prove more powerful or superior in a struggle contest or conflict
exist or be widespread in a particular area or at particular time
examples: Justice prevailed when the innocent man was finally released from prison
The home team prevailed in overtime with a last-second winning goal
Cooler temperatures prevail in the mountain regions throughout the summer months
Traditional customs still prevail in many rural villages despite modern influences

definitions: see or show something before it is officially available to the general public
examples: Critics preview new movies before they open in theaters nationwide Friday
Students can preview next semester's courses online starting Monday morning

definitions: hunt and kill other animals for food as a natural behavior
take advantage of or exploit someone especially when they are vulnerable
examples: Eagles prey on small mammals and fish in their natural habitat
Large cats prey on zebras and antelopes in the African savanna
Scammers prey on elderly people who live alone without family support
Bullies often prey on students who appear shy or physically weaker

definitions: make a small hole in something with a sharp point or instrument
cause a sudden sharp pain or stinging sensation to someone or something
examples: She pricked her finger while sewing the delicate silk fabric yesterday
Use a fork to prick holes in the pie crust before baking
The thorns pricked his hands as he pruned the rose bushes
My conscience pricked me about lying to my best friend yesterday

definitions: make oneself look neat and formal in an excessively proper or precise way
examples: She primmed her hair before meeting her boyfriend's parents for dinner
The students primmed themselves for the important school photograph session

definitions: arrange or deal with things in order of importance giving most attention to most important
examples: Successful managers prioritise tasks based on deadlines and business impact
We need to prioritise patient care over administrative paperwork duties

definitions: arrange or deal with things in order of importance giving most attention to most important
examples: Emergency rooms prioritize patients based on severity of medical conditions
Students should prioritize studying for exams over social activities this week

definitions: transfer a business or industry from public to private ownership and control
examples: The government plans to privatize the national railway system next year
Many countries privatized their telecommunications companies in the 1990s successfully

definitions: officially prove a will is valid through legal process after someone dies
examples: The court will probate her grandmother's will next month in chambers
Lawyers must probate the estate before distributing assets to beneficiaries legally

definitions: investigate or examine something thoroughly especially to discover information or truth
physically explore or examine something with an instrument or tool carefully
examples: Journalists probe corruption allegations against several government officials this week
Detectives probe the crime scene for clues about the suspect's identity
The dentist probed my teeth checking for signs of decay carefully
Scientists probe the ocean floor with special underwater robotic vehicles

definitions: announce something officially or publicly in a formal way with conviction or authority
examples: The mayor proclaimed a day of celebration for the city's anniversary
The president proclaimed victory after the election results were confirmed officially

definitions: supervise students during an examination to ensure rules are followed and prevent cheating
examples: Teachers take turns to proctor final exams during examination week schedules
Graduate students often proctor undergraduate tests to earn extra income monthly

definitions: obtain something especially with care effort or difficulty through special arrangement or means
examples: The museum procured several rare paintings for their new exhibition opening
It's difficult to procure certain medications without proper medical prescriptions

definitions: poke someone or something with a finger or pointed object repeatedly
urge or encourage someone to do something they are reluctant about
examples: The farmer prodded the cattle with a stick to move them along
She prodded the campfire coals to revive the dying flames quickly
His parents constantly prod him to find a better paying job
The coach prodded the team to practice harder for the championship

definitions: treat something sacred with irreverence disrespect or contempt through words or actions
examples: Vandals profaned the cemetery by knocking over several old gravestones maliciously
Some felt the comedian profaned religious symbols in his controversial performance

definitions: claim something often falsely or declare something openly that may be doubted
declare faith in or allegiance to a religion belief or principle publicly
examples: He professes to know nothing about the missing money from accounts
Many politicians profess concern for the poor during election campaign seasons
Monks profess their faith through vows of poverty chastity and obedience
She professes Buddhism after years of studying Eastern philosophical traditions

definitions: arrange or schedule activities or events according to a plan or timetable
input instructions into a computer or other machine to control its operation
examples: The conference organizers programme speakers for three days of presentations
Schools programme extracurricular activities throughout the entire academic year carefully
Engineers programme robots to perform complex manufacturing tasks with precision daily
She programmes websites using various coding languages for international clients

definitions: slip forward or down out of normal position especially of body organs
examples: The veterinarian treated a cow whose uterus had prolapsed after birthing
Heavy lifting can cause pelvic organs to prolapse in some individuals

definitions: increase rapidly in number or amount spreading quickly over time or across areas
examples: Social media apps proliferate faster than regulators can monitor their impact
Cancer cells proliferate uncontrollably when the body's defenses fail completely

definitions: make something last longer by extending its duration beyond the usual or expected time
examples: Don't prolong the meeting unnecessarily when all topics have been covered
Medical treatments can prolong life but not always improve its quality

definitions: walk in a public place for pleasure or display especially in a leisurely way
examples: Couples promenade along the beachfront boardwalk every Sunday afternoon together
The graduates will promenade across the stage to receive their diplomas

definitions: promote or make widely known an idea or cause through official announcement or decree
examples: The organization promulgates new safety standards for the manufacturing industry annually
Universities promulgate research findings through academic journals and conference presentations

definitions: say words correctly making the proper sounds especially in a particular way
declare or announce something formally or officially with authority
examples: She learned to pronounce French words by listening to native speakers
Can you pronounce this medical term correctly for the class please
The judge pronounced the defendant guilty of all charges yesterday afternoon
The doctor pronounced him dead at the scene of the accident

definitions: support or hold up something with an object placed underneath or against
lean something against a support to prevent it from falling over
examples: Workers prop the sagging ceiling with wooden beams until repairs begin
She propped the door open with a heavy book while moving furniture
He propped his bicycle against the garage wall before entering the house
Students prop their textbooks on desk stands for easier reading angles

definitions: spread and promote an idea belief or knowledge to many people widely
breed specimens of a plant or animal by natural processes
examples: Social media helps propagate both accurate information and dangerous misinformation rapidly
Missionaries traveled worldwide to propagate their religious beliefs to new communities
Gardeners propagate roses by taking cuttings from healthy parent plants annually
Some plants propagate naturally through underground runners or root systems
